body:
@vilmospapp, @chrismattmann, it seems that Tomcat (where I saw such problem) is quite paranoidal about thread locals. Its check is usually done before GC throw out weak references (`ThreadLocalMap.Entry` is a `WeakReference`), so Tomcat logs something like:

```
06-Oct-2014 19:37:41.009 SEVERE [RMI TCP Connection(14)-127.0.0.1] org.apache.catalina.loader.WebappClassLoader.checkThreadLocalMapForLeaks The web application [] created a ThreadLocal with 
  key of type [org.apache.tika.parser.image.ImageMetadataExtractor$ExifHandler$1] (value [org.apache.tika.parser.image.ImageMetadataExtractor$ExifHandler$1@3a97b29a]) 
  and a value of type [java.text.SimpleDateFormat] (value [java.text.SimpleDateFormat@6b2ed43a]) 
  but failed to remove it when the web application was stopped. 
  Threads are going to be renewed over time to try and avoid a probable memory leak.
```

If I force several GCs after application undeploy this thread local is usually collected. I think you can remove PR #17 and let this PR merge into tika.

To test that it's collected I created simple servlet:

``` java
@WebServlet(name = "t", urlPatterns = {"/t"})
public class AppServlet extends HttpServlet {
  @Override
  protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest req, HttpServletResponse resp) throws ServletException, IOException {
    Metadata metadata = new Metadata();
    try {
      new ImageMetadataExtractor(metadata).parseJpeg(new File("/home/gross/repo/tl-test/test.jpeg"));
    } catch (SAXException | TikaException e) {
      throw new ServletException(e);
    }
    resp.getWriter()
        .append(metadata.get(TIFF.ORIGINAL_DATE));
  }
}
```

Which is deployed to tomcat 8 with VM running with `-XX:+PrintGCDetails -XX:+TraceClassUnloading` to see class unloading and GC executions. To force GC I used `jcmd <pid> GC.run` or _Perform GC_ in `jvisualvm`.

So, you have SDF that is created on first `get()` in `handleDateTags(...)` and removed in finally block. Then there's no reason to store it in `ThreadLocal`. It's more inefficient than local variable.

I think that private static SimpleDateFormat plus some syncronized format method for it will be more efficient and obvious method to fix issue.

``` java
static class ExifHandler implements DirectoryHandler {
  private static final SimpleDateFormat DATE_UNSPECIFIED_TZ = new SimpleDateFormat("yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss");

  private synchronized String formatDateWithoutTimeZone(Date datetime) {
    return DATE_UNSPECIFIED_TZ.format(datetime);
  }

  // ...
  public void handleDateTags(Directory directory, Metadata metadata) {
    // ...
    String datetimeNoTimeZone = formatDateWithoutTimeZone(...);
  }
}
```

